BILL NO. 3742 By: Harris of the House
2
and
3
Daniels of the Senate
4
5
6 An Act relating to criminal procedure; creating the
Due Process Protection Act of 2026; amending 22 O.S.
7 2021, Section 258, as amended by Section 2, Chapter
269, O.S.L. 2022 (22 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section 258),
8 which relates to preliminary examinations and
proceedings; requiring the disclosure of certain
9 information to the defense; providing construing
provision; authorizing the court to set disclosure
10 deadline under certain circumstances; amending 22
O.S. 2021, Section 2002, as amended by Section 2,
11 Chapter 327, O.S.L. 2025 (22 O.S. Supp. 2025, Section
2002), which relates to the Oklahoma Criminal
12 Discovery Code; directing the state to disclose
certain evidence prior to the initial appearance of
13 defendants; requiring the disclosure of evidence
favorable to the defendant; requiring disclosure
14 despite its form; declaring the ongoing duty to
disclose information; increasing time limitation for
15 introducing testimony from informants and
codefendants; updating informant references;
16 modifying scope of certain defined term; clarifying
disclosure duties of defendants; establishing time
17 limitation for completing discovery issues; providing
an exception to certain witnesses; providing for
18 noncodification; and providing an effective date.
19
20
21 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
22 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law not to be
23 codified in the Oklahoma Statutes reads as follows:
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3742 Page 1

1 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Due Process
2 Protection Act of 2026".
3 SECTION 2. AMENDATORY 22 O.S. 2021, Section 258, as
4 amended by Section 2, Chapter 269, O.S.L. 2022 (22 O.S. Supp. 2025,
5 Section 258), is amended to read as follows:
6 Section 258. First: A. The witnesses must be examined in the
7 presence of the defendant, and may be cross-examined by the
8 defendant. On the request of the district attorney, or the
9 defendant, all the testimony must be reduced to writing in the form
10 of questions and answers and signed by the witnesses, or the same
11 may be taken in shorthand and transcribed without signing, and in
12 both cases filed with the clerk of the district court, by the
13 examining magistrate, and may be used as provided in Section 333 of
14 this title. In no case shall the county be liable for the expense
15 in reducing such testimony to writing, unless ordered by the judge
16 of a court of record.
17 Second: B. The district attorney may, on approval of the county
18 judge or the district judge, issue subpoenas in felony cases and
19 call witnesses before the district attorney and have them sworn and
20 their testimony reduced to writing and signed by the witnesses at
21 the cost of the county. Such examination must be confined to some
22 felony committed against the statutes of the state and triable in
23 that county, and the evidence so taken shall not be receivable in
24 any civil proceeding. A refusal to obey such subpoena or to be
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3742 Page 2

1 swor n or to testify may be punished as a contempt on complaint and
2 showing to the county court, or district court, or the judges
3 thereof that proper cause exists therefor.
4 Third: C. No preliminary information shall be filed without the
5 consent or endorsement of the district attorney, unless the
6 defendant be taken in the commission of a felony, or the offense be
7 of such character that the accused is liable to escape before the
8 district attorney can be consulted. If the defendant is discharged
9 and the information is filed without authority from or endorsement
10 of the district attorney, the costs must be taxed to the prosecuting
11 witness, and the county shall not be liable therefor.
12 Fourth: D. The convening and session of a grand jury does not
13 dispense with the right of the district attorney to file complaints
14 and informations information, conduct preliminary hearings and other
15 routine matters, unless otherwise specifically ordered, by a written
16 order of the court convening the grand jury; made on the court's own
17 motion, or at the request of the grand jury.
18 Fifth: E. There shall be no preliminary examinations in
19 misdemeanor cases.
20 Sixth: F. A preliminary magistrate shall have the authority to
21 limit the evidence presented at the preliminary hearing to that
22 which is relevant to the issues of: (1) whether the crime was
23 committed, and (2) whether there is probable cause to believe the
24 defendant committed the crime. Once a showing of probable cause is
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3742 Page 3

1 made the magistrate shall terminate the preliminary hearing and
2 enter a bindover order; provided, however, that the preliminary
3 hearing shall be terminated only if the state made available for
4 inspection law enforcement reports within the prosecuting attorney's
5 knowledge or possession at the time to the defendant five (5)
6 working days prior to the date of the preliminary hearing. The
7 district attorney shall determine whether or not to make law
8 enforcement reports available prior to the preliminary hearing. If
9 reports are made available, the district attorney shall be required
10 to provide those law enforcement reports that the district attorney
11 knows to exist at the time of providing the reports, but this does
12 not include any physical evidence which may exist in the case. This
13 provision does not require the district attorney to provide copies
14 for the defendant, but only to make them available for inspection by
15 defense counsel. In the alternative, upon agreement of the state
16 and the defendant, the court may terminate the preliminary hearing
17 once a showing of probable cause is made.
18 Seventh: G. 1. Upon request of the defense, the state shall
19 disclose the following not less than thirty (30) days prior to the
20 preliminary hearing:
21 a. initial and supplemental reports in the possession of
22 the district attorney,
23 b. summaries of any interviews that are intended to be
24 introduced at preliminary hearing which have not been
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3742 Page 4

1 provided or summarized in reports provided to the
2 defense,
3 c. summaries of any videos that are intended to be
4 introduced at preliminary hearing which have not been
5 provided or summarized in reports provided to the
6 defense,
7 d. summaries of victim interviews which have not been
8 provided or summarized in reports provided to the
9 defense,
10 e. video or audio recordings intended to be introduced at
11 preliminary hearing of any statements made by an adult
12 victim, adult witness, or the defendant,
13 f. photographs intended to be introduced at preliminary
14 hearing,
15 g. photographic lineups intended to be introduced at
16 preliminary hearing,
17 h. deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) reports intended to be
18 introduced at preliminary hearing, and
19 i. 9-1-1 calls intended to be introduced at preliminary
20 hearing.
21 2. Nothing in this subsection shall be construed to require the
22 disclosure of a recording of a statement of a minor.
23 3. Notwithstanding the thirty-day disclosure requirement
24 provided for in this subsection, if the preliminary hearing is set
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3742 Page 5

1 in c lose proximity to the request date, the court may set a
2 reasonable time for disclosure under the provisions of this
3 subsection.
4 H. A preliminary magistrate shall accept into evidence as proof
5 of prior convictions a noncertified copy of a Judgment and Sentence
6 when the copy appears to the preliminary magistrate to be patently
7 accurate. The district attorney shall make a noncertified copy of
8 the Judgment and Sentence available to the defendant no fewer than
9 five (5) days prior to the hearing. If such copy is not made
10 available five (5) days prior to the hearing, the court shall
11 continue the portion of the hearing to which the copy is relevant
12 for such time as the defendant requests, not to exceed five (5) days
13 subsequent to the receipt of the copy.
14 Eighth: I. The purpose of the preliminary hearing is to
15 establish probable cause that a crime was committed and probable
16 cause that the defendant committed the crime.
17 Ninth: J. The preliminary hearing must be set within nine (9)
18 months from the initial appearance of the defendant. If
19 commencement of the preliminary hearing is delayed past the nine-
20 month time limit, a show cause hearing shall be scheduled by the
21 court to show reason for the delay. If the court fails to find good
22 cause for the delay, the court shall schedule a preliminary hearing
23 as soon as practicable.
24
