1 SECTION 3. AMENDATORY 22 O.S. 2021, Section 2002, as
2 amended by Section 2, Chapter 327, O.S.L. 2025 (22 O.S. Supp. 2025,
3 Section 2002), is amended to read as follows:
4 Section 2002. A. Disclosure of Evidence by the State.
5 1. Upon request of the defense, the state shall disclose the
6 following:
7 a. unless otherwise prohibited by law, the names and
8 addresses, phone numbers, and, if available to the
9 state, email addresses of witnesses which the state
10 intends to call at trial interviewed, identified, or
11 known by any member of law enforcement or any member
12 of the office of the prosecutor during the course of
13 the prosecution, together with their relevant, written
14 or recorded statement, if any, or, if none,
15 significant summaries of any oral statement. Phone
16 numbers and email addresses of victims of domestic
17 violence, sexual assault, child abuse, stalking, or
18 violations of a protective order may be maintained by
19 the office of the district attorney and made available
20 to defense counsel upon request,
21 b. all law enforcement reports made in connection with
22 the particular case, including initial and
23 supplemental reports by any person or agency involved
24 in the investigation of the case, photographs,
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3742 Page 7

1 diagrams, vehicle dashboard camera and body camera
2 video, and audio and video recordings directly related
3 to the case,
4 c. any all written or recorded statements and the
5 substance of any all oral statements made by the
6 accused or made by a codefendant to any member of law
7 enforcement, any member of the office of the
8 prosecutor, or any other person or agency involved in
9 the investigation of the case,
10 d. any all photographs and lineup materials taken or used
11 during a lineup procedure, and any notes or reports
12 made resulting from the lineup procedure. The duty to
13 disclose lineup materials includes all pre-lineup and
14 post-lineup instructions given to the witness, as well
15 as recordings made prior to, during, or following the
16 lineup procedure, and all initial and subsequent
17 suspect descriptions obtained from eyewitnesses,
18 e. all reports or statements of examinations or tests
19 made by experts in connection with the particular
20 case, including results of physical or mental
21 examinations and of, preliminary or presumptive tests
22 and screening results, scientific tests, experiments,
23 or comparisons, polygraph testing, all raw data,
24 worksheets, laboratory notes, diagrams, and peer
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3742 Page 8

1 review notes or reports and any such records stored
2 electronically, and all records of proficiency testing
3 relating to any testing or analysis,
4 e. any
5 f. all books, papers, documents, photographs, tangible
6 objects, buildings or places which the prosecuting
7 attorney intends to use in the hearing or trial or
8 which were obtained from or belong to during the
9 accused course of the investigation,
10 f.
11 g. any record of prior criminal convictions of the
12 defendant, or of any codefendant codefendants, and
13 witnesses that law enforcement or the prosecutor has
14 interviewed who the state intends to testify,
15 g. Oklahoma State Bureau of Investigation (OSBI) rap
16 sheet/records check
17 h. background checks, including criminal history, on any
18 witness listed by the state or the defense as a
19 witness who will testify at trial, as well as any
20 convictions of any witness revealed through additional
21 record checks if the defense has furnished Social
22 Security numbers or date of birth for their witnesses,
23 except OSBI rap sheet/record checks shall not provide
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3742 Page 9

1 date of birth, Social Security number, home phone
2 number or address,
3 i. dispatch records, 9-1-1 calls, or other emergency
4 service calls related to the crime. The prosecution
5 may withhold the names and identifying information of
6 any victim who contacted 9-1-1 or other emergency
7 services provided; however, an application for a
8 protective order pursuant to the provisions of
9 paragraph 1 of subsection E of this section may be
10 made. If the prosecution intends to call such person
11 as a witness at a trial or hearing, the prosecution
12 shall disclose the name and contact information, as
13 available to the state, of such witness no later than
14 thirty (30) days before such trial or hearing or as
15 soon as practicable, and
16 j. the name and work affiliation of all law enforcement
17 personnel who have evidence or information relevant to
18 any offense charged or to any potential defense
19 thereto. Unless the court rules otherwise for good
20 cause shown information, pursuant to the provisions of
21 this subparagraph, relating to undercover personnel
22 may be withheld and redacted from discovery materials
23 without the need to file a motion and upon written
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3742 Page 10

1 notification by the prosecution that such information
2 has not been disclosed.
3 2. The state shall provide the defendant any all evidence in
4 its possession which may be favorable to the defendant if such
5 including, but not limited to, evidence is material to either that:
6 a. negates the guilt or punishment of the defendant as to
7 a charged offense,
8 b. reduces the degree of or mitigates the culpability of
9 the defendant as to a charged offense,
10 c. supports a potential defense to a charged offense,
11 d. impeaches the credibility of a testifying prosecution
12 witness, or
13 e. undermines evidence of the identity of the defendant
14 as a perpetrator of a charged offense.
15 Information under the provisions of this paragraph shall be
16 disclosed whether or not such information is recorded in tangible
17 form and irrespective of whether the prosecutor credits the
18 information.
19 The prosecutor shall have an ongoing duty to disclose such
20 information within a reasonable amount of time upon its discovery.
21 3. The prosecuting attorney's obligations under this standard
22 extend to:
23 a. material and information in the possession or control
24 of members of the prosecutor's staff,
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3742 Page 11

1 b. any information in the possession of law enforcement
2 agencies that regularly report to the prosecutor of
3 which the prosecutor should reasonably know, and
4 c. any information in the possession of law enforcement
5 agencies who have reported to the prosecutor with
6 reference to the particular case of which the
7 prosecutor should reasonably know.
8 4. a. If the state intends to introduce testimony of a
9 jailhouse an informant, including a codefendant, the
10 state shall disclose at least ten (10) thirty (30)
11 days prior to trial:
12 (1) the complete criminal history of such informant,
13 including any dismissed charges,
14 (2) any deal, promise, inducement or benefit that the
15 state or law enforcement agency has made or may
16 make in the future to the jailhouse informant in
17 connection with the testimony of such informant,
18 (3) the specific statements or recordings made by the
19 suspect or defendant and the time, place and
20 manner of the disclosure to the jailhouse
21 informant,
22 (4) all other filed cases in which the state intended
23 to introduce the testimony of the jailhouse
24 informant in connection with a deal, promise,
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3742 Page 12

1 inducement or benefit, the nature of the deal,
2 promise, inducement or benefit, and whether the
3 testimony was admitted in the case,
4 (5) whether at any time the jailhouse informant
5 recanted the testimony or statement, and if so, a
6 transcript or copy of such recantation, if any,
7 and
8 (6) any other information relevant to the credibility
9 of the informant.
10 b. Each district attorney's office shall maintain a
11 central record that tracks each case in which the
12 state intended to introduce the testimony of the
13 jailhouse informant against a suspect or defendant in
14 connection with a deal, promise, inducement or
15 benefit, the nature of the deal, promise, inducement
16 or benefit and whether such testimony or statements
17 were admitted in the case. Such record shall be sent
18 to the District Attorneys Council which shall maintain
19 a statewide record of such information. Records
20 maintained pursuant to this paragraph shall only be
21 accessible to prosecutors and shall not be subject to
22 the Oklahoma Open Records Act. By September 15 of
23 each year, the District Attorneys Council shall
24 publish an annual report of aggregate, de-identified
ENGR. H. B. NO. 3742 Page 13

